Introduction¶

Summary: This project looks at implementing an algorithm to solve the problem of assigning students to courses and finding timeslots for the courses being offered so that the students can attend the courses they wish to take.

In this first part:

  • I created the raw data on course requests for the students
  • Split the courses into different sections
  • Developed a sequential adjacency list data structure for section conflicts based on the student course requests

Implementation¶

Purpose:
Determine which courses each student will take. The courses are numbered from 1 to C. The courses for each student will be determined based on a random number generator with different distributions. Part 1 will then split the courses into distinct sections and then determine which sections of which courses must be scheduled at a different time from each other to avoid conflicts in the students' schedules.

Take in these inputs:

  • C = Number of courses being offered (MAX = 10,000)
  • S = Number of students (MAX = 100,000)
  • K = Number of courses per student. (MAX = C)
  • SectionSize = the target size of a section
  • SPLIT = BASIC | ADVANCED
  • DIST = UNIFORM | 2-TIERED | 4-TIERED | NORMAL (my custom function)

Return the output:

  • C = Number of courses being offered
  • S = Number of students
  • K = Number of courses per student
  • SectionSize = the target size of a section
  • SPLIT = BASIC | ADVANCED
  • DIST = UNIFORM | 2-TIERED | 4-TIERED | NORMAL
  • M = number of distinct pair-wise section conflicts
  • T = total number of pair-wise section conflicts
  • E[] = adjacency list of distinct section conflicts (length = 2M)
  • P[] = Pointer for each section I, 1 <= I <= N denoting the starting point in E[] of the list of sections in conflict with section I. That is, the conflicts for section I are indicated in locations E[P[I]], E[P[I]+1], ..., E[P[I+1]-1].

Course Assignment Function¶

Function Purpose:¶

Assign courses to students in a manner that satisfies the given specified distribution for the courses.

Distributions:¶

  • Uniform Distribution:
    • Notes: 
        All courses have equal probability. For each student, we'll want to extend the range of courses they
  can choose from to the entire course list and pick only k for each student.
  • 2-Tiered Distribution:
    • Notes: 
        The 2-tiered distribution assumes that the first 10% of courses have 50% of the probability distribution. The remaining 90% of courses have 50% of the probability distribution as well.
  • 4-Tiered Distribution:
    • Notes: 
        The 4-tiered distribution assumes
  - first 25% of courses have 40% probability
  - next 25% have 30% probability
  - next 25% has 20% probability
  - last 25% has 10% probability
  • Normal Distribution:
    • Notes: 
        Gaussian/Normal distribution: 
  - 68% of the values lie within 1 standard deviation of the mean
  - 95% lie within 2 standard deviations
  - 99.7% lie within 3 standard deviations
  references: https://introcs.cs.princeton.edu/python/appendix_gaussian/

# Shuffle function adapted from: https://cs.stackexchange.com/questions/47338/whats-a-uniform-shuffle 
# This function will change the arrangement of the list, but not the elements 
def shuffle(list):
    n = len(list) #number of items into the list
    for i in range(n-1):
        #pick a random index from the list 
        j = random.randint(i, n-1) 
        #swap the current item in the list with the item at the randomly selected index
        (list[i], list[j]) = (list[j], list[i])
In [6]:
def sample(low, high, size):
    sample_range = list(range(low, high))
    shuffle(sample_range)
    sample_list = sample_range[0:size]
    return sample_list
In [7]:
def sample_wo_duplicates(listobj, size):
    sample_range = listobj
    sample_list = []
    shuffle(sample_range)
    for i in range(size):
        if(sample_range[i] not in sample_list):
            sample_list.append(sample_range[i])
        else:
            rand_index = random.randint(i, len(sample_range)-1)
            rand_item = (sample_range[rand_index])
            while (rand_item in sample_list):
                rand_index = random.randint(i, len(sample_range)-1)
                rand_item = (sample_range[rand_index])
            sample_list.append(rand_item)
    return sample_list

def distribute_courses(dist, students, c, k):
    # Data structures (return variables) for these assignments:
    # student_enrollment -- type: dict, item = keypair : (key = each student : pair = courses student is taking)
    # course_enrollment -- type: dict,  item = (key = each course : pair = students in the course)
    # selected_courses -- type: list, item = tuple : (course number, # of students in course)
    
    student_enrollment, course_enrollment, selected_courses = ({}, {}, []) #initialize data structures
    
    if(dist == 'UNIFORM'): 
        for student in students:
            course_selection = []
            
            # randomly pick k classes for each student
            # setting the population to the range(0,c) ensures an equal course seleciton probability
            course_selection = sample(0,c,k)
            
            # populate a dictionary of the students assigned to each course
            for course_num in course_selection:
                if(bool(course_enrollment.get(course_num)) == False):
                    course_enrollment[course_num] = [student]
                else:
                    course_enrollment[course_num].append(student)
            
            # populate a dictionary of the courses assigned to each student        
            student_enrollment[student] = sorted(course_selection)
            
            # populate a list that keeps track of how many students are in each course
            for course in course_selection:
                selected_courses.append(course)
    if(dist == '2-TIERED'):
        #determine first 10% of courses 
        first_10pct = round(c*.1)
        
        for student in students:
            course_selection, course_selection_first50, course_selection_last50 = ([], [], [])

            course_selection_first50 = list(range(0, first_10pct))
            shuffle(course_selection_first50)
            
            course_selection_last50 = list(range(first_10pct, c)) 
            shuffle(course_selection_last50)
            
            for picked_course in range(k): 
                #Randomly select from one of the 2 lists created above
                #By using random.randint with 2 options, this means each option has a 50% chance
                #of getting selected since each integer created has an equal probability
                list_to_pick_from = random.randint(0,1)
                if (list_to_pick_from == 0):
                    # check if list is empty before trying to pick a course from it
                    # if list is empty, pick from other list
                    if(len(course_selection_first50) > 0):
                        course_selection.append(course_selection_first50.pop())
                    else:
                        course_selection.append(course_selection_last50.pop())
                else:
                    if(len(course_selection_last50) > 0):
                        course_selection.append(course_selection_last50.pop())
                    else:
                        course_selection.append(course_selection_first50.pop())
            
            for course_num in course_selection:
                if(bool(course_enrollment.get(course_num)) == False):
                    course_enrollment[course_num] = [student]
                else:
                    course_enrollment[course_num].append(student)

            student_enrollment[student] = course_selection
                
            
            for course in course_selection:
                selected_courses.append(course)
    
    if(dist == '4-TIERED'):
        weightedlist = []
        #determine indexes of each quartile 
        first_quartile = round(c/4)
        second_quartile = first_quartile * 2
        third_quartile = first_quartile * 3
        last_quartile = c
        
        quartile1 = list(range(0, first_quartile)) #add 4 of these to list to simulate 40%
        quartile2 = list(range(first_quartile, second_quartile)) #add 3 of these to list to simulate 30%
        quartile3 = list(range(second_quartile, third_quartile)) #add 2 of these to list to simulate 20%
        quartile4 = list(range(third_quartile, last_quartile)) #add 1 of these to list to simulate 10%
        
        weightedlist= (quartile1 + quartile1 + quartile1 + quartile1 + quartile2 + quartile2 + quartile2
                    + quartile3 + quartile3 + quartile4)
        
        for student in students:
            course_selection = sample_wo_duplicates(weightedlist, k)
        
            for course_num in course_selection:
                if(bool(course_enrollment.get(course_num)) == False):
                    course_enrollment[course_num] = [student]
                else:
                    course_enrollment[course_num].append(student)
            
            student_enrollment[student] = sorted(course_selection)
            
            for course in course_selection:
                selected_courses.append(course)
    
    if(dist == 'NORMAL'):
        #get median/mean/mode (these should be equal) course number
        if((c%2) == 0):
            mu = round(c/2)
        else:
            mu = round(c/2) + 1
        

        #obtain sigma value (standard deviation)
        sigma = mu/3
        neg3_sigma = round(mu - sigma*3)
        neg2_sigma = round(mu - sigma*2)
        neg1_sigma = round(mu - sigma)
        pos1_sigma = round(mu + sigma)
        pos2_sigma = round(mu + sigma*2)
        pos3_sigma = round(mu + sigma*3)
        
        #sigma1 ~ 68%; sigma2 (neg and pos) ~ 13.5% * 2; sigma3 (neg and pos) ~ 2.5% * 2
        sigma1_selections = list(range(neg1_sigma,pos1_sigma))
        
        #combine the positive and negative parts
        sigma2neg_selections = list(range(neg2_sigma,neg1_sigma))
        sigma2pos_selections = list(range(pos1_sigma,pos2_sigma))
        #sigma2_selections = sigma2neg_selections + sigma2pos_selections
        
        #combine the positive and negative parts 
        sigma3neg_selections = list(range(0,neg2_sigma))
        sigma3pos_selections = list(range(pos2_sigma,C))
        sigma3_selections = sigma3neg_selections + sigma3pos_selections
        
        weightedlist = []
        #Instead of the 21 list additions below, I could have also used 10 additions
        #where sigma1 was added 7 times, sigma2 added 2 times, and sigma3 added once
        #sigma 3 = 5%; sigma 2 = 27% ~ 6 * 5%; sigma 1 = 68% ~ 14 * 5%
        weightedlist = sigma3_selections
        for i in range(3):
            weightedlist += sigma2neg_selections
        for i in range(3):
            weightedlist += sigma2pos_selections
        for i in range(14):
            weightedlist += sigma1_selections
            
        for student in students:    
            course_selection = sample_wo_duplicates(weightedlist, k)
            
            #create a dictionary of the students assigned to each course
            for course_num in course_selection:
                if(bool(course_enrollment.get(course_num)) == False):
                    course_enrollment[course_num] = [student]
                else:
                    course_enrollment[course_num].append(student)

            #assign the courses to each student
            #the lists contain the indices of the course names defined in the list, courses
            student_enrollment[student] = sorted(course_selection)
            for course in course_selection:
                selected_courses.append(course)
                
    return selected_courses, student_enrollment, course_enrollment

def determine_courses(c, s, k, sectionsize, split, dist):     
    # create list data structure for each student 
    students = [] 
    for student_num in range(s): 
        students.append(student_num)
        
    # based on the determined distribution, randomly assign courses to each student 
    selected_courses, student_enrollment, course_enrollment = distribute_courses(dist, students, c, k)
    
    # convert the list into a counter which will show the course number and the number of students in each course
    selected_courses = sorted(collections.Counter(selected_courses).items())

    return selected_courses, student_enrollment, course_enrollment

Section Split Function¶

This split should work to ensure both the minimum and maximum conditions are met. If the minimum capacity is not met in the final section split, you could get rid of the last section and distribute its students among the other sections without exceeding the maximum capacity.

In [10]:
def section_split(s, c, sectionsize, split, course_selections, student_enrollment, course_enrollment): 
    course_sections = {} # sections per course
    
    # student_section_schedule = courses that the student is taking with the section numbers 
    # will be a dictionary of the courses a student is taking and the session number associated with it
    # ex: {student0 : { course0: section1, course19: section3, course3: section1}}
    student_section_schedule = {} 
    
    minsize = round(2/3*sectionsize)
    maxsize = round(4/3*sectionsize)
    
    #split mainly if maximum section size is exceeded (4/3 * sectionsize)
    if (split == "BASIC"):
        #-----------Number of Sections Determination--------------------------------
        for course in course_selections: #c[0,1] = [course num, students in course]
            sections = 0 #number of sections for each course 
            
            #check if you should have multiple sections
            if (course[1] <= maxsize):
                sections = 1    
            else:  
                if((course[1] % sectionsize) < minsize):
                    sections = int(floor(course[1]/sectionsize))
                else:
                    sections = int(course[1]/sectionsize) + 1
                    
            course_sections[course[0]] = sections #save the number of sections to each course number

        #-----------Section Split Determination--------------------------------
        #Go through students in each course and assign them to a section
        for course, students in course_enrollment.items():
            # There aren't enough students in the course to create another section or 
            # the calculation above determined there should only be one section
            # containing all students enrolled in the course
            if ((len(students) <= sectionsize) or (course_sections[course] == 1)):
                section_num = 0
                #go ahead and assign all students taking this course to section0
                for student in students:
                    #create section identifier with the course number followed by the section number
                    section_id = str(course) + '_' + str(section_num) 
                    
                    #populate the dictionary that tracks the student and the sections they're in
                    if(bool(student_section_schedule.get(student)) == False): 
                        student_section_schedule[student] = [section_id]
                    else:
                        student_section_schedule[student].append(section_id)
            
            #----At this point splitting into multiple sections is required----
            # Note: If you create a new section only if you reach the maximum size, 
            #       this doesn't guarantee that each section will meet the minimum size. 
            #       This is why I proceed with the following method. 
            #
            # Method: 
                #1. Fill each section to 2/3*sectionsize
                #2. Then distribute remaining students until they're all distributed
            else: 
                # list of students taking specific course 
                students_list = students 
                # predetermined list of the number of students that should be in each course
                num_of_sections = course_sections[course] 
                # dictionary of the course sections and the students assigned to them 
                section_assignments = {}
                
                # get optimal section size
                # This is the base amount to start assigning students to sections.
                # Get a chunk of students to be in the particular section, then get the remaining 
                # students (fill_to) and go back and forth refilling each existing section.
                optimal_sectionsize = 0
                
                if (((len(students) % sectionsize) <= minsize) or 
                    ((sectionsize * num_of_sections) > len(students))):
                    optimal_sectionsize = minsize
                    fill_to = maxsize - minsize
                else:
                    optimal_sectionsize = sectionsize
                    fill_to = maxsize - sectionsize
                
                #initial splitting
                for section in range(num_of_sections):
                    section_students = sample_wo_duplicates(students, optimal_sectionsize)
                    section_assignments[section] = section_students
                    for student in section_students:
                        students_list.remove(student)
                        
                #split remaining students if any 
                for section in range(num_of_sections):
                    while(len(students_list) > 0):
                        if(len(students) < fill_to):
                            fill_to = len(students)
                        #fill each existing session until maximum size reached
                        section_students = sample_wo_duplicates(students, fill_to)
                        section_assignments[section] += section_students
                        for student in section_students:
                            students_list.remove(student)
                
                #Now assign each student to a section 
                for section, students in section_assignments.items():
                    section_id = str(course) + '_' + str(section)
                    #empty dictionary 
                    for student in students: 
                        if(bool(student_section_schedule.get(student)) == False): 
                            student_section_schedule[student] = [section_id]
                        else:
                            student_section_schedule[student].append(section_id)
            
    else:
        print("Advanced Split") #Extra credit; chose not to implement for this part
        #find students with similar classes to each other and put them in a section together
        
    return student_section_schedule

def get_section_conflicts(s, course_sections, student_enrollment):
    conflicts = []
    
    #get pairwise combinations 
    for i in range(s):
        #print(len(list(itertools.combinations(student_enrollment[i], 2))))# = K(K-1)/2 checked correctly!
        conflicts.extend(list(itertools.combinations(course_sections[i], 2)))
    T = len(conflicts) 
    
    #removes duplicates / method should be O(M) space
    start = t.time()
    unique_conflicts = []
    unique_conflicts = list(set(conflicts[i] for i in range(len(conflicts))))
    M = len(unique_conflicts)
    end = t.time()
    remove_duplicates_runtime = end - start
    #prepare E[] and P[] arrays

    #will assign the conflicts between both elements in the pair
    #ex: (item1, item 2) 
    #--> item1 will have item2 as a conflict
    #--> item2 will have item1 as a conflict
    E = defaultdict(list)
    for i in range(len(unique_conflicts)):
        if unique_conflicts[i][1] not in E[unique_conflicts[i][0]]:
            E[unique_conflicts[i][0]].append(unique_conflicts[i][1])
        if unique_conflicts[i][0] not in E[unique_conflicts[i][1]]:
            E[unique_conflicts[i][1]].append(unique_conflicts[i][0])
    
    conflict_adjacencies = dict(E)
    
    #reset E 
    E = []
    P = [] 
    e_index = 0
    item_counter = 0
    num_items = len(conflict_adjacencies.items())
    
    #(course_conflicts[0,1]: [course, conflicting courses]
    for key, value in conflict_adjacencies.items(): 
        if (len(E) == 0):
            P.append(e_index)
        E += value
        e_index += len(E)
        item_counter += 1
        if(item_counter != num_items):
            P.append(len(E))
    
    return list(unique_conflicts), T, M, conflict_adjacencies, E, P, remove_duplicates_runtime

def part1(c, s, k, sectionsize, split, dist):
    course_selections, student_enrollment, course_enrollment = determine_courses(c, s, k, sectionsize, split, dist)
    course_sections = section_split(s, c, sectionsize, split, course_selections, student_enrollment, course_enrollment)
    
    #course-wise conflicts 
    #course_conflicts, T, M, adjacency_list, E, P = get_conflicts(s, course_sections, student_enrollment)
    
    suppress_outputs = input("Suppress adjacency list outputs? Enter Y: ")
    
    #section-wise conflicts
    course_conflicts, T, M, adjacency_list, E, P, remove_duplicates_runtime = get_section_conflicts(s, course_sections, student_enrollment)
    
    print("OUTPUT:\n")
    print("Parameters: \n")
    print("C:", c)
    print("S:", s)
    print("K:", k)
    print("SectionSize:", sectionsize)
    print("SPLIT:", split)
    print("DIST:", dist)
    print("\nStudent Assignment Calculations:")
    print("T:", T)
    print("M:", M)
    if(suppress_outputs != "Y"):
        print("-------------------------------------")
        print("Adjacency_list", adjacency_list)
        print("-------------------------------------")
        print("E[]:", E)
        print("\nP[]:", P)

# will return execution times in seconds 
def part1_timing(c, s, k, sectionsize, split, dist):
    start = t.time()
    course_selections, student_enrollment, course_enrollment = determine_courses(c, s, k, sectionsize, split, dist)
    end = t.time()
    
    determine_courses_runtime = end - start 
    
    start = t.time()
    course_sections = section_split(s, c, sectionsize, split, course_selections, student_enrollment, course_enrollment)
    end = t.time()
    
    section_split_runtime = end - start

    #section-wise conflicts
    course_conflicts, T, M, adjacency_list, E, P, remove_duplicates_runtime = get_section_conflicts(s, course_sections, student_enrollment)

    
    print("Course Assignment Runtime:", determine_courses_runtime)
    print("Section Split Runtime:", section_split_runtime)
    print("Remove Duplicates Runtime: ", remove_duplicates_runtime)

CSE 5370: Course Timeslot and Student Assignment Project

Part 2

Introduction¶

Summary: This project looks at implementing an algorithm to solve the problem of assigning students to courses and finding timeslots for the courses being offered so that the students can attend the courses they wish to take. In this second part, I create 3 different methods of coloring a graph. Vertices of different colors will be course-sections that conflict with each other.

Implementation¶

Purpose:
Use three different methods for ordering the vertices in the graph: Smallest Last Vertex Ordering and 2 other methods of your choice. Then assign a color (scheduling time) to each vertex in the order determined so that it doesn't conflict with the other vertices already colored. Then compare the different ordering methodologies based on the following criteria: asymptotic running time, asymptotic space requirement, total number of colors needed, and a report on any other interesting metric.

Take in these inputs:

  • C = Number of courses being offered
  • S = Number of students
  • K = Number of courses per student
  • SectionSize = the target size of a section
  • SPLIT = BASIC | ADVANCED
  • DIST = UNIFORM | 2-TIERED | 4-TIERED | NORMAL
  • M = number of distinct pair-wise section conflicts
  • T = total number of pair-wise section conflicts
  • E[] = adjacency list of distinct section conflicts (length = 2M)
  • P[] = Pointer for each section I, 1 <= I <= N denoting the starting point in E[] of the list of sections in conflict with section I. That is, the conflicts for section I are indicated in locations E[P[I]], E[P[I]+1], ..., E[P[I+1]-1].

Return the output: Input parameters except E[] and P[]

  • C = Number of courses being offered
  • S = Number of students
  • K = Number of courses per student
  • SectionSize = the target size of a section
  • SPLIT = BASIC | ADVANCED
  • DIST = UNIFORM | 2-TIERED | 4-TIERED | NORMAL
  • For each vertex (session) the color, original degree, (and degree when deleted for the smallest last ordering). These should be printed in the order colored.
  • Total number of colors used
  • The average original degree
  • Maximum "degree when deleted" value for the smallest last ordering, and the size of the terminal clique for the smallest last ordering
  • Additional summary data

Graph Functions¶

Vertex Data Structure¶

A vertex (class session) will store 4 fields of data.

  • Field 1 : session number
  • Field 2 : P(I) = pointer to edge list
  • Field 3 : current degree, -1 when deleted, color value
  • Field 4 : pointers for doubly-linked list of vertices of same current degree, pointer for order deleted list

I'm going to make each field like a key for the above values. For a field with multiple values, the values will be stored to a list.

In [15]:
class vertex:
    all_vertices = defaultdict(list)
    def __init__(self, sessionNumber="", currentDegree=0, color="none", color_num=0):
        self.session = sessionNumber
        self.degree = currentDegree
        self.color = color 
        self.color_num = color_num
        self.dwd = -1
        vertex.all_vertices[self.session].append(self)
    def getColor(self):
        return self.color
    def setColor(self, color):
        self.color = color
    def getColorNum(self):
        return self.color_num
    def setColorNum(self, color_num):
        self.color_num = color_num
    def getDegree(self):
        return self.degree
    def setDWD(self, dwd):
        self.dwd = dwd
    def printVertex(self): 
        print("vertexNo",self.session) 
        print("degree",self.degree) 
        print("color hex: %s number: %s" % (self.color, self.color_num))
    def printLastVertex(self): 
        print("vertexNo",self.session) 
        print("original degree",self.degree) 
        print("degree when deleted",self.dwd) 
        print("color hex: %s number: %s" % (self.color, self.color_num))
    @classmethod
    def findByVertexNo(cls, vtx): 
        return vertex.all_vertices[vtx][0]

#Will take a graph and return the degree of a particular vertex or vertices
#Returned graph will be in the form of { session : degree }
def getDegree(graph, vertices):
    vertexDegrees = defaultdict(list)
    
    for vertex in vertices:
        degree = len(graph[vertex])
        vertexDegrees[vertex] = degree
    
    return vertexDegrees

def getSameDegree(graph):
    x = getDegree(graph,list(random_graph.keys()))

    #create a new graph by degree
    sameDegree = {}
    checkedDegrees = []
    
    #session and the degree of the vertex
    sorted_x = sorted(x.items(), key=operator.itemgetter(1))
    
    vertexColors = {}
    for pair in sorted_x:
        degree = pair[1]
        vertex = pair[0]
        if(len(sameDegree) == 0):
            sameDegree[degree] = [vertex]
            checkedDegrees.append(degree)
        else:
            if(degree == checkedDegrees[len(checkedDegrees)-1]):
                sameDegree[degree].append(vertex)
            else:
                sameDegree[degree] = [vertex]
                checkedDegrees.append(degree)
                
    return sameDegree

def getAvgDegree(adjacencies):
    degreeGraph = getDegree(adjacencies, list(adjacencies.keys()))
    degree_sum = 0
    for session, degree in degreeGraph.items():
        degree_sum += degree
    avg_degree = degree_sum / len(degreeGraph)
    
    return avg_degree

import operator
from collections import OrderedDict
#color the vertices by order given by graph 
def colorGraph(graph):
    vertexColors = {}
    adjacencyColors = {}
    
    #Create a random color (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/16819222/how-to-return-dictionary-keys-as-a-list-in-python)
    #initialize color array with one color
    r = lambda: random.randint(0,255)
    hexcode = ('#%02X%02X%02X' % (r(),r(),r()))
    usedColors=[hexcode]
 
    #check if color matches colors of the adjacent vertices
    for vtx, adjacencies in graph.items():
        
        #vertex isn't connected to any other vertex
        if(len(adjacencies) == 0):
            vertexColors[vtx] = usedColors[0]
            vertex.findByVertexNo(vtx).setColor(usedColors[0])
            vertex.findByVertexNo(vtx).setColorNum(1)
            
        #vertex has at least one neighbor and the nodes must be different colors
        else:
            adjacent_colors = []
            #look for all set colors (values that aren't "none")
            #vertex can't be these colors
            for a in adjacencies:
                vertex_color = vertex.findByVertexNo(a).getColor()
                if(vertex_color != ""):
                    adjacent_colors.append(vertex_color)
            uc_num = 1
            for uc in usedColors:
                #you find a color that isn't being used in adjacent vertices and can use it
                if (uc not in adjacent_colors):
                    vertexColors[vtx] = uc
                    vertex.findByVertexNo(vtx).setColor(uc)
                    vertex.findByVertexNo(vtx).setColorNum(uc_num)
                    break
                #you went through all available colors and now must create a new color
                if(uc == usedColors[len(usedColors)-1]):
                    r = lambda: random.randint(0,255)
                    #make sure to get a unique color that hasn't been used before
                    while(r in usedColors):
                        r = lambda: random.randint(0,255)
                    hexcode = ('#%02X%02X%02X' % (r(),r(),r()))
                    usedColors.append(hexcode)
                    vertexColors[vtx] = hexcode
                    vertex.findByVertexNo(vtx).setColor(hexcode)
                    vertex.findByVertexNo(vtx).setColorNum(len(usedColors))
                    break
                
                uc_num += 1
    colors = []
    for color_assignment in vertexColors.items():
        colors.append(color_assignment[1])
        
    totalColors = len(usedColors)
    
    
    return totalColors, colors, usedColors

In [20]:
def getTerminalClique(vstack, dwdlist):
    #go through dwdlist from the end to the front and look for the
    #increasing pattern
    clique_size = 0
    tclique = []
    for idx in range(len(dwdlist)-1):
        if ((dwdlist[idx] + 1) == dwdlist[idx+1]):
            clique_size += 1
            tclique.append(vstack[idx])
        else:
            clique_size += 1
            tclique.append(vstack[idx])
            break
            
    print("Terminal Clique", tclique)
    return (clique_size)

Vertices Ordering Method 1: Smallest Last Vertex Ordering¶

  1. Pick vertex of minium degree
  2. Push on stack
  3. Remove from graph
  4. Repeat until done
  5. Pop from stack and color

To find the terminal clique, I thought you might have to check through all the adjacencies of the vertices to be deleted, ensure they were all equal degrees and search for a decreasing sequence where the next list of adjacencies for the next vertex were equal and a degree less from the last vertex. However, I found a much easier way to check for this pattern, which is looking at the vertex at the end(the one that will be deleted); if the degree sequence of the vertices being deleted starts going down incrementally to 0, this is the terminal clique.

In [162]:
%%time 
#will get time of entire function, including time to produce outputs

def smallestLastVertex(c, s, k, sectionsize, split, dist, m, t, e, p, adjacencies): 
    start = myTime.time()
    vertexStack = []
    degreeGraph2 = {} 
    G = defaultdict(list)
    vertexDSStack = [] #added
    dwd = [] #added (degrees when deleted)
    
    #get the degrees for each vertex 
    degreeGraph = getDegree(adjacencies, list(adjacencies.keys()))
    x=degreeGraph
    degreeGraph = sorted(x.items(), key=operator.itemgetter(1), reverse=True)
    #----------If you need to convert the ordered dict back into a dict----
    for pair in degreeGraph:
        degreeGraph2[pair[0]] = pair[1]
    #----------If you need to convert the ordered dict back into a dict----
   
    for v in range(len(degreeGraph2)):
        minVertex = degreeGraph[len(degreeGraph)-1][0]
        dwd.append(degreeGraph[len(degreeGraph)-1][1]) # added
        del degreeGraph[len(degreeGraph)-1]
        vertexStack.append(minVertex)
        #update the degrees of adjacent vertices
        minVertexList = adjacencies[minVertex]
        
        for vtx in minVertexList:
        #decrease the degree of these adjacent vertices
            if (vtx not in vertexStack):
                degreeGraph2[vtx] = degreeGraph2[vtx] - 1
        del degreeGraph2[minVertex]
        
        degreeGraph = sorted(degreeGraph2.items(), key=operator.itemgetter(1), reverse=True)

    vertexStack.reverse()
    dwd.reverse() #added
    
    dwd_index = 0 # added
    for v in vertexStack:
        v_adjacencies = adjacencies[v]
        G[v] = v_adjacencies 
        vertexDSStack.append(vertex(v, getDegree(adjacencies, [v])[v], "", 0)) #added
        vertex.findByVertexNo(v).setDWD(dwd[dwd_index])#added
        dwd_index += 1 #added
    end = myTime.time()
    ordering_time = end - start 
    
    print("\nSmallest Last Vertex")
    
    #Color the graph
    start = myTime.time()
    totalColors, vertexColors, usedColors = colorGraph(G) #added
    end = myTime.time()
    coloring_time = end - start 
    
    #Outputs 
    
    if(OUTPUT2_VERBOSE == True):
        for v in vertexStack:
            vertex.findByVertexNo(v).printLastVertex()   
        
    print("\n")
    print("Total number of colors used:", totalColors)
    print("Rounded Average Degree:", round(getAvgDegree(adjacencies)))
    print("Maximum Average Degree When Deleted:", max(dwd))
    print("Terminal Clique Size:", getTerminalClique(vertexStack, dwd))
    
    if(OUTPUT2_EXTRA == True):
        plotDegreeOrder(vertexDSStack)
        colorCount(vertexColors, usedColors)
    if(OUTPUT2_GRAPH == True):
        drawGraph(G, True, vertexColors)
    
    return G, ordering_time, coloring_time

Vertices Ordering Method 2: Random Vertex Ordering¶

In [163]:
%%time

def randomVertex(c, s, k, sectionsize, split, dist, m, t, e, p, adjacencies):
    start = myTime.time()
    print("\nRandom Vertex")
    # You really only need the adjacency graph, e 
    # 1. initialize the vertex list
    V = []
    # 2. initialize the graph that will be returned
    G = defaultdict(list)
    # 3. initialize one list to keep track of vertex ordering 
    #    and another list of vertices with the session and the color and degree of it 
    vertexStack = [] 
    vertexDSStack = []

    # 3. add each session from the adjacency graph as a vertex to the vertex list 
    for session, conflicting_sessions in adjacencies.items(): 
        V.append(session)
        
    # 4. for each vertex in the list, 
    #    - 4.1 randomly pick a vertex from the vertex list
    #    - 4.2 get the adjacent vertices
    #    - 4.3 assign the adjacent vertices to the selected vertex and make this an item of the graph
    #    - 4.4 remove the vertex from the vertex list
    while len(V) > 0:
        randomIndex = random.randint(0, len(V)-1)
        vpick = V[randomIndex]
        vpick_adjacencies = adjacencies[vpick]
        G[vpick] = vpick_adjacencies 
        vertexStack.append(vpick)
        vertexDSStack.append(vertex(vpick, getDegree(adjacencies, [vpick])[vpick], "", 0))
        V.remove(vpick)
    end = myTime.time()
    ordering_time = end - start
    
    start = myTime.time()
    # 5. Color the graph
    totalColors, vertexColors, usedColors = colorGraph(G)
    end = myTime.time()
    coloring_time = end - start 
    
    # 6. Print the output data:
    #    - Inputs except for e and p
    #    - For each vertex, the color and degree (printed in the order that the vertices are colored)
    #    - Total number of colors used
    #    - The average degree
    #    - Graph indicating the degree on the vertical axes and the order colored on the x-axis
    #    - Additional Summary Data
    
    if(OUTPUT2_VERBOSE == True):
        for v in vertexStack:
            vertex.findByVertexNo(v).printVertex()   
        
    print("\n")
    print("Total number of colors used:", totalColors)
    print("Rounded Average Degree:", round(getAvgDegree(adjacencies)))
    if(OUTPUT2_EXTRA == True):
        plotDegreeOrder(vertexDSStack)
        colorCount(vertexColors, usedColors)
    if(OUTPUT2_GRAPH == True):
        drawGraph(G, True, vertexColors)
    
    # 7. return
    return G, ordering_time, coloring_time

Wall time: 12.2 s

def plotDegreeOrder(stack):
    degree = []
    index = 1
    indices = []
    for item in stack:
        degree.append(item.getDegree())
        indices.append(index)
        index += 1
    plt.title("Vertex Degree in the Order of Coloring")
    plt.plot(indices,degree, 'bo') 
    plt.xlabel("order of coloring")
    plt.ylabel("degree") 
    plt.show()

def colorCount(vertexColors, usedColors):
    color_dictionary = {}
    color_tuples = [] 
    vcs = []
    color_num = 1
    for color in usedColors:
        c_tuple = str(color_num) + " : " + color
        color_tuples.append(c_tuple)
        color_dictionary[color] = c_tuple
        color_num += 1
    
    for color_code in vertexColors:
        vcs.append(color_dictionary[color_code])
        
    plt.hist(vcs)

    plt.title("Count of Vertex Colors")
    plt.xlabel("color")
    plt.ylabel("count") 
    plt.show()
